<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1034,1658]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,388,1034,1060]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
The male of 
<taxonomicName box="[555,777,1034,1059]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Acrophotopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="campylognatha">
<emphasis box="[555,777,1034,1059]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">A. campylognatha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has greatly dilated mandibles that are deeply excised ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[273,347,1072,1098]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,278,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,197,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,197,1739]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Head, anterior view. 1. Acanthophotopsis falciformis; 2. Acrophotopsis campylognatha; 3. Odontophotopsis acmaea; 4. O. armata; 5. O. aufidia; 6. O. bellona; 7. O. biramosa; 8. O. clypeata; 9. O. inconspicua; 10. O. mamata; 11. O. melicausa; and 12. O. quadrispinosa." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196848/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[330,347,1072,1098]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
), lacks mesosternal processes, has a flattened hypopygidium that is carinate anterolaterally and has genitalia that are distinctive in having the paramere and cuspis dorsoventrally flattened and the cuspis straight (
<figureCitation box="[254,390,1146,1172]" captionStart="FIGURES 44 – 48" captionStartId="17.[151,272,1292,1316]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,179,1265]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,179,1279]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 44 – 48. Sphaeropthalma mankelli, sp. nov.: 44. Head, anterior view; 45. Habitus; and 46. Apex of wing. Acrophotopsis campylognatha: 47. genitalia, dorsal view (scale 0.5 mm) and 48. Close up of cuspis (scale 0.2 mm) (Fig. 47. from Pitts &amp; McHugh 2002)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196853/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs 
<number box="[313,390,1146,1172]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="47.48">47, 48</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
